          <p>Your practitioner has seen hundreds or thousands of cases like yours. They know which method works best for different situations, and they're trained to adapt if needed. Your job is to show up - their job is to figure out the best way to help you.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- Simple Method Overview -->
    <section class="methods-section">
      <div class="container">
        <h2 class="section-title">The Three Main Methods (Simple Explanation)</h2>
        <p class="section-subtitle">You don't need to memorize this, but here's a basic overview of what your practitioner might choose:</p>

        <div class="methods-simple">
          <div class="method-card modern">
            <div class="method-header">
              <div class="method-icon">üî¨</div>
              <h3>Microsuction</h3>
              <div class="method-badge gold">Most Popular</div>
            </div>
            <div class="method-content">
              <h4>What it is:</h4>
              <p>Gentle suction using a tiny tube, with magnification so the practitioner can see exactly what they're doing.</p>

              <h4>Why practitioners like it:</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Safest method available</li>
                <li>No water means no mess</li>
                <li>Works for almost everyone</li>
                <li>Very precise control</li>
              </ul>

              <div class="patient-experience">
                <h4>What it feels like:</h4>
                <p>"Like a gentle vacuum cleaner in your ear. Bit noisy but not uncomfortable. Over before you know it." - Sarah, 34</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="method-card traditional">
            <div class="method-header">
              <div class="method-icon">üíß</div>
              <h3>Irrigation</h3>
              <div class="method-badge blue">Time-Tested</div>
            </div>
            <div class="method-content">
              <h4>What it is:</h4>
              <p>Warm water gently flushes the wax out. Much more controlled and safer than old-style ear syringing.</p>

              <h4>Why practitioners choose it:</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Very thorough cleaning</li>
                <li>Often less expensive</li>
                <li>Quick and effective</li>
                <li>Good for softer wax</li>
              </ul>

              <div class="patient-experience">
                <h4>What it feels like:</h4>
                <p>"Like a warm shower for your ears. Bit wet obviously, but quite soothing. Amazing how much came out!" - David, 67</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>

          <div class="method-card specialist">
            <div class="method-header">
              <div class="method-icon">üîß</div>
              <h3>Manual Removal</h3>
              <div class="method-badge orange">Specialist Cases</div>
            </div>
            <div class="method-content">
              <h4>What it is:</h4>
              <p>Tiny instruments to carefully extract wax piece by piece. Used for tricky situations where other methods aren't suitable.</p>

              <h4>Why it's sometimes needed:</h4>
              <ul>
                <li>Very hard, stuck wax</li>
                <li>Unusual ear canal shapes</li>
                <li>When combined with other issues</li>
                <li>Patient-specific requirements</li>
              </ul>

              <div class="patient-experience">
                <h4>What it feels like:</h4>
                <p>"Bit more involved than the others, but totally painless. Fascinating to watch the practitioner work." - Emma, 45</p>
              </div>
            </div>
          </div>
        </div>

        <div class="methods-truth">
          <h3>The Honest Truth</h3>
          <p>All three methods work excellently when performed by qualified practitioners. The "best" method is simply whichever one your practitioner thinks will work most effectively for your specific situation. Don't overthink it - they've got this.</p>
        </div>
      </div>
    </section>

    <!-- What Actually Happens Section -->
    <section class="appointment-reality-section">
      <div class="container">
        <h2 class="section-title">What Your Appointment Actually Looks Like</h2>
        <p class="section-subtitle">Forget complicated medical descriptions. Here's what really happens from the moment you arrive:</p>

        <div class="appointment-journey">
          <div class="journey-step">
            <div class="step-number">1</div>
            <div class="step-content">
              <h3>You Arrive & Get Comfortable (5 mins)</h3>
